# Project Structure

- Prefer feature-based organization inside `src`, while preserving the architecture boundaries of `domain`, `application`, `infrastructure`, `presentation`, and `shared`.
- Keep the bootstrap files at the root of `src`, such as `app.ts`, `server.ts`, and `socket.ts`, when they compose the application.
- Use `src/presentation/http` for REST routes, controllers, request validators, and HTTP middleware.
- Use `src/presentation/socket` for Socket.IO namespaces, gateways, event handlers, and socket auth helpers.
- Use `src/presentation/docs` or `src/docs` for Swagger/OpenAPI setup and schema registration.
- Keep feature modules grouped by business area when helpful, such as `auth`, `users`, `health`, `notifications`, or `chat`.
- Place environment parsing and app configuration in `src/shared/config`.
- Place logger, error classes, response helpers, and common constants in `src/shared`.
- Keep reusable adapters for `bcryptjs`, `jsonwebtoken`, `uuid`, `moment`, and external services in focused modules instead of scattering direct usage.
- Avoid mixing route registration, business logic, and persistence code in the same folder or file.
- Use Python for scripts in `scripts/` (e.g. test helpers, dev utilities). Prefer standard library; add `requests` only when needed.
